============================================================
  PHILOSOPHY
============================================================

Concept:      Stoicism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Focus only on what is in your control; accept all else with equanimity
Philosopher:  Marcus Aurelius/Epictetus
Example:      Illness is not in your control; your response to it is

Concept:      Nihilism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Life has no inherent meaning; values are human inventions
Philosopher:  Nietzsche (diagnosed)
Example:      Without objective grounding, all moral frameworks are invented

Concept:      Utilitarianism
Branch:       Ethics
Definition:   Maximize pleasure minimize pain across all sentient beings
Philosopher:  Jeremy Bentham
Example:      Felicific calculus: measure units of pleasure and pain

============================================================
  QUESTION & ANSWER PAIRS
============================================================

Q1: What is metabolism?
A1: Metabolism is all chemical reactions in an organism
     that maintain life: catabolism (breaking molecules for
     energy) and anabolism (building complex molecules from
     simple ones).

Q2: What is a programming language?
A2: A programming language is a formal set of instructions
     for computers. High-level languages (Python, Java) are
     human-readable; low-level (Assembly) are closer to
     machine code.

Q3: What is gravity?
A3: Gravity is an attractive force between all masses.
     Newton described it as F = Gm1m2/r². Einstein refined
     it as spacetime curvature in general relativity.

Q4: What is plate tectonics?
A4: Earth's crust is divided into tectonic plates that move
     on the mantle. Their interactions create earthquakes,
     volcanoes, mountains, and ocean trenches over millions
     of years.

Q5: What is machine learning?
A5: Machine learning enables systems to learn from
     experience without being explicitly programmed, using
     data to improve performance automatically.

